<dl id="s14060aq"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us14" href="#s14060aq">Oxen of the Sun: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s14all.htm#s14060aq">sector 60(aq)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> abbreviature / exantlation / equable catachresis</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I doubt whether I myself, a good many years ago, did not make unwise concessions in admitting exceptions to Browne on the score of Latinism and of <mark>catachresis</mark> of words <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> when he substitutes &lsquo;clarity&rsquo; for &lsquo;clearness&rsquo;, when he pours upon the vulgar head the perhaps to it doubtfully precious balms of <mark>&lsquo;abbreviature&rsquo; and &lsquo;exantlation&rsquo;</mark>; even when he has such traps for the unwary as <mark>&lsquo;equable&rsquo;</mark> in the sense of &lsquo;equitable&rsquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> he is not only manipulating the <i>xena</i>, the &lsquo;strange&rsquo; words which strike the sense <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> but is actually and deliberately adding to the sonority and harmony of his phrase. <small> George Saintsbury, <a name="GSAH" href="/udra/udex.htm#gsah"><cite title="source">A History of English Prose Rhythm</cite></a> (1912), 182 (on Thomas Browne)</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
